If you’re looking for a very traditional Egyptian experience, this is the perfect spot. The place is decorated so beautifully and the food is delicious. Ordered a lamb chop with rice and veggies and was absolutely not disappointed. The cook is a great guy. Loved.
This is quite the experience in little egypt. Food is delicious but best part is the chef is the coolest dude that exists. The setup also has the right vibe.

Probably the coolest chef you will ever get to  meet, super friendly, does everything from A to Z by himself on the spot! The most authentic & super delicious Egyptian food in NYC! Always changing & great variety menu options, must try!
Nice traditional Egyptian food and atmosphere, the chef's hospitality is amazing

One man show , nice little place , very friendly owner , he does everything all by himself. Cooks, and serves, quite an experience,  just like going to your parents home and ask them for the food you love , no menu , just few items which makes it simple, loved the place as if you just walked into old egypt , decorations , music , loved the whole thing
Curb appeal

authentic food. very delicious and feels like eating at home back in Egypt. we are visiting NYC. We had lamb dish, chicken dish and molukhia with grilled chicken. my kids loved the food. the owner is very friendly. the decor of the place was top. i would  definitely come again.

Literally hole in the wall. Difficult to find their sign. Small space for seating but they seated us outside (NYC new norm). Food was amazing. I ordered their Alexandria liver which is better than what I have even tasted in Egypt. Also tried their Lamb Tajin which was amazing, the meat was so tender and spices were perfect. Their Hawawshi was also very tasty and all was very affordable. Dinner for two cost around 60, definitely worth it and would definitely go back.
The food is absolutely delicious. I tried their liver, haweoshi and tawooj. My favoured was haweoshi. The chief takes his time making the food so expect  to wait for your food!!!
Great outdoor scenery and excellent tea
Delicious, authentic Egyptian food cooked by an interesting, friendly, highly skilled chef.  The interior is very exotic and fascinating!

The decor here was brilliant. Service was great too. Food was not good at all. Very bland and expensive for what it is. It was just one person preparing, serving and taking care of everything since we came as a large group so I wasn't too harsh on the review. If you want good food, better to go to a cart. It was a nice experience here but I wouldn't recommend it.
A very special place, the quality of food is very intense and surprise us. The dishes and their flavor were outstanding.

This is definitely a hidden gem in NYC. I don’t think I can name any place like this in the city. The restaurant chef/owner Mustafa runs everything. He spent 5 years designing the interior from the drawings to the tiles. He cooks amazing homemade Egyptian food. He even waits on you (tells you the specials, brings drinks/food) - he is definitely a man of many talents. On top of that, he’s really sweet and he really cares that you enjoy the food and experience. Think like a mom & pop kind of shop - something really rare to get in NYC. The only thing you have to do is wait a bit for meals to come out cause he really cares that they’re fresh.  I recommend getting some appetizers while you wait for the main dishes to come out. We ordered Sahara Mix, Mombar (Appetizers) lamb tagine, and dejaj fel-foron (Mains). We wiped our plates clean. Unique taste. Really fresh. Can’t recommend this place enough!
5 stars for the freshness of food. Taste!! Very funky. Time stuck in the 70s. Super friendly chef.
Amazing food, top quality dishes, very sweet staff, but CASH ONLY. Keep that in mind. Super worth it.c
Words cannot describe the meal I had there and the fact that it is BYOB isn't bad either
food is delicious and authentic, servers were very helpful too. will come back :)
The best food in New York for Egyptian food
Leave plenty of time to savor the amazing atmosphere and experience that feels very much like a restaurant in another part of the world.

Quite the experience!  What a gem.  Lamb tagine and hummus were spectacular.  One tip - come here prepared for a slower pace of things because the owner (whose art also decorates the walls from corner to corner) also prepares your meal and serves it to you.  A very memorable meal all around.
The Incredible chef/owner...the ambiance..the authentic food, the friendly chef and patrons. Love the individually prepared meals.  I can't say enough good things.  Spectacular!
Delicious, authentic cuisine. The chef is incredibly professional and friendly and has great suggestions for a first-time Egyptian food experience
The food is so delicious! The place is like a piece of art! But it’s over priced!
Amazing!!!!!
Very nice
The food here is so gooooooooooooood. I recommend everybody I know to this place. The smell that comes from the kitchen is the best thing ever.
It s a nice place.

This place made me remember my time back at Egypt. I worked in Egypt for over 2 years and I loved the food there. This place completley replicates the Egyptian taste that i love. I will be coming this place again.

This is as close to home made authentic Egyptian food as you're going to get outside an Egyptian home, with the added benefit of a proprietor/cook/server (same person!) who is a really talented chef and a nice person. We were a group of 4 and had besara and liver as appetizers (5 stars).  Two of us had the lamb (5 stars), one person had mezza collection (4 stars) and one had artichoke (4 stars). We've been there before and will go there again.
Mombar has bad food in my
This place is always amazing. Huge portions at reasonable prices and the decor/vibes are nothing I've ever experienced.

This place is amazing. The food is delicious. Don’t expect to come hear for a fast meal. The chef takes his time to work his magic and everything is cooked from scratch. It is BYOB. I have been coming here for years. This is truly a hidden gem in queens.
Very good ☺ and clean,, tasty medl Easter foods,, good food and good price,, good atmosphere,, frined staff,, recommended to anyone he likes different cultures food,,

The food was exceptional, the chef is the owner and the artist who designed everything in the restaurant. After we ate he told us about his work and showed us around the dining area, some of the items he used for art he made when he was a kid. We will definitely be back with friends, wonderful taste of Egypt in Astoria!
Authentic Egyptian. Top item was the Mombar.
Oh I love this place. Food is awesome fresh and home made. Takes long to prepare but it is amazing food.
(Translated by Google) It is very native attended by its owner, the food excellent.  (Original) Es muy autóctono atendido por su propietario, la comida excelente.

Absolute gem of a place! The man who runs it did all the art and decoration here. Food is in huge portions and everything is delicious. He also has off menu recommendations -- the sweetbread was amazing

Amazing food. We had the lamb sheikh and the hummus platter and the beet salad for appetizers with cold hibiscus tea. Excellent! Then we had the lamb shank with spinach and the stuffed chicken with rice. Delish! We over ordered but thats ok :) it was 4 ppl and the bill was nominal. Will be going again. The chef is praiseworthy,  very kind.
Authentic Egyptian food. Highly recommend!

Place was quiet on a Saturday evening. Owner (I assume) was very nice. Food was tasty, the couscous was a little dry for my liking, the lamb shank was tender and the spinach was delicious. The hot hibiscus tea was a tart delight.
The food is excellent, the interior decoration is eclectic, and the owner is the chef. Fantastic and I’ve been eating here for years!!

Fun,  unique,  affordable,  colorful spot for Middle Eastern food in a busy ethnic area of Queens. Owner-chef makes all the art, which is half the experience. Large portions, under  $20. No booze - BYO - but wine openers are available. Egyptian-style suitable for timid American palates. Big tables for large groups. Quiet when we arrived at 6pm. Probably bustling at 9pm on Saturday night.  Great couscous+veggies. Loved the lamb
Awesome 👍. The owner is very sweet and caring, he is wonderful. The food is great and delicious 👌.
Love the inside of this place
Go for the food, stay to admire the decor.
Such a delicious food simply !
Delicious food and friendly service. Lamb cheeks were fantastic. Rabbit was great.
Consistently delicious meals and top notch service. Intimate interesting interiors. BYOB is great for groups but I often stop after work for solo dining and have hot mint tea with my meal.
Great experience, delicious food, amazing decor (the owner created all the art pieces. always ask for the specials!
Amazing meal. Tasted like I was home and every corner has art that I wanted to take home.
The food is great, the art all made by the chef/owner is original and the timeless experience of escaping into Cairo, just a train into Astoria is priceless!
Mustafa is a genius, just like his brother Ali up the street (Kabab Cafe). While Ali focuses on cuisine from Alexandria, Mustafa focuses on southern Egyptian specialties. Wonderful place.
I was busy eating the delicious food, so we didn't take any pictures. Trust me on this one, when he says cheeks, say "yesssss"
Has great food and the seasoning was amazing. I completely loved I hope u do to!!
you must spend time to observe every table, floor, art work..the food is delish..

The food was absolutely amazing, the tilapia was full of flavor and done immediately when ordered which ensured everything was fresh and wonderful, the chef was very nice and hospitable, and the dessert was wonderfully light and delicious
Love this place and the owner. Food made from scratch and delish
The food was very good, and the staff are attentive and make great recommendations. The place has really cool decorations too!
(Translated by Google) A place with flavors and smells that would take you to Egypt  (Original) Un lugar con sabores y olores que te llevaría a Egipto
Very good place and delicious food!

I do not need to give great detail especially in light of the many great reviews. We were a party of 12. The food was great. The service was more than acceptable.  The decor and outside entry was quirky and unique. All in all it was like wonderful home cooking.

BYOB. Great place with a very friendly owner. The decorations and feel of the place is wonderful and the food is delicious. Just be warned that the food may take a while as the owner does everything himself from cooking to taking orders. Come here with company and make sure you aren't starving when you get there because you need to wait for your meal
Great experience. It's one guy who does it all, very home like feel to it.  Food was fantastic and everyone around was very friendly.  BYOB and no corkage fee!
Amazing food , owner takes pride in what he serves
Always just so delicious. I've brought 10 or so people here so far on different visits!

Fantastically authentic spot - it feels like you're eating in someone's home, especially since owner / chef Mustafa is also the one bringing the food out and chatting with you. Always listen to his specials, and ask for recommendations! Food comes out slowly, so if you're in a rush you might want to come back when you have time to enjoy this gem.
Excellent food and a pretty sweet environment, but not fast paced. A spot where you will look sit down and don’t rush the meal. The hummus, foul and baba gannoush appetizer is really good too!
Good
Delicious food, fascinating decor, charming owner (ask him about his art!)

This restaurant is run by the incredibly friendly owner and one helper in the kitchen. The food is delicious and lovingly prepared but if it's a busy night be prepared to wait because there is no staff. We don't have any problems waiting because the food and ambiance is worth it. The restaurant is decorated with all kinds of eclectic items collected by the owner and we always find something new and neat to speculate about. Always wait to decide on your meal based on the specials. And best in mind that this establishment is cash-only and BYOB.

My fiance and I went for a walk, not intending to get dinner, but when we passed this gorgeous little building on Steinway Street, we were immediately drawn to it. We peeked our heads in and saw a cozy, ecclectically designed restaurant that made us feel like we were no longer a handful of blocks from home, but traveling to a distant land where all the troubles of life no longer matter. It was a slow night for the restaurant, which made our visit that much more special. The owner was very friendly and welcoming and recommended the perfect dishes for us to try. My fiance got the lamb shank while I opted for the sea bass. Our meals were fantastic - perfect blends of spices, tender meats falling off the bones, variety of carefully seasoned vegetables served with heaps of rice and couscous. For two people who weren't even planning on getting dinner, we finished every last bite on our plates and then relaxed with a hot cup of mint tea while discussing everything from family lineage to the state of the world with our gracious host. This is not a typical NYC restaurant. It's warm and unpretentious, the owner welcomes you like family, and the food tastes like grandma has been up since daybreak preparing it. Unbeknownst to me, Mombar has been there for 18 years and I can't believe it was my first visit. It definitely won't be my last.
Very good authentic food a atmosphere. The decoration is simply amazing.

I moved to the U.S. from Egypt three years ago and ever since, I have been trying to find good Egyptian restaurants (and failing). Mombar is the closest taste I could find to home. It's a family-run restaurant ans the owner/cook is a very friendly man from Alexandria. Molokhia is my favorite, along with the Mombar. You'd probably end up spending around $30-40 but the food is so worth it.

A quiet place in Steinway street. The food is super authentic, not too expensive and served in decent portion. The chef/host is super friendly and took his time to explain us the menu. Also, do not expect to have your food ready in 5min, it's more like a slow food kind of place but that's why I want to go back there some other time. (Cash only but there is an ATM next door)
Nice food, great service. Felt like home.
Had the best time ever. Quaint and very artsy.  The owner receives you with a warm welcome
Nice decor ... and delicious food
(Translated by Google) Mat3am khateer wel akl mestahel.  (Original) Mat3am khateer wel akl mestahel.
Small place.  Great food

What a gem! Trekked out the Queens to visit this place on a friend's recommendation and definitely worth it. Food was truly delicious and authentic - from Quail appetizers to seabass and steak. But what makes this place special is the story behind it - the owner (also the chef) has hand decorated everything from the table tops to the lampshades to the bathroom to create a delightful, intimate and unique space. He is happy to chat to you about his work too. Cannot recommend more highly if you want an escape from boring mass-produced chain food.
Amazing food. Lamb cheeks are my favorite. Friendly service as well.

A neighbourhood gem! I've been here three times and on each occasion the owner, a nice old man greeted me, showed me to my table, explained the specials, took my order, cooked it and served it! The wait may be a little long but this is what slow food is all about! Fantastic Egyptian food with vegetarian options. My favourites are the Besara or Sahara for starters then the eggplant and lamb with couscous for the mains. Don't forget the hibiscus tea! The ambiance is also really interesting and felt like I was in Cairo!
The worst ever , don’t go to their
Food is fantastic! I love this place. A must-have for foodies.

The main attraction is the decor of walls and tables. It feels home as there is a single all-round chef who serves, takes order and cooks it for you. It has a menu but not much use of it as he cooks whatever he gets for that day. But the food is fresh which is the main thing

Mombar is a special restaurant.  It is off the beaten path and worth the journey. The place looks like Egyptian Pee Wee's playhouse with unusual and interesting art all over the place.  The chef is such a nice man and he puts so much passion into his cooking. The food all tastes like it is made with love. On my most recent trip I had the Egyptian lamb chops and the warm artichoke salad. Both were spectacular in flavor and preparation.   Tip: don't go here if you are in a hurry as the service is run at a very relaxed pace. Also this place is BYOB so bring a bottle of wine with you if you like!
Great sandwiches
Food is very good, everything was delicious. Services is slow.
Food was delicious. Friendly staff too! It was cash only, so make sure you have it!

(Translated by Google) We can eat healthy, they are professional, and have meals from all over the Arab world .. try mlokhiya b araneb .. it's a special taste  (Original) On peut y manger sain, ils sont professionnels, et ont de repas du partout du monde arabe.. essayez le mlokhiya b araneb.. c’est un goût spécial
Best Egyptian food in the country. It's a hole in the wall and very easy to miss walking by it! Everything taste great!
Small restaurant with full of delicious food, we order fish and baked stuffed chicken. Worth coming into this place.
Delicious food, personal service, unusual (but cool) ambiance. BYOB, lots of vegetarian and vegan options Terrific spot!

This place is LEGIT!  It seems like the kind of place people may shy away from upon first glance... But those people would be missing out!  If you like garlic, eggplant, hummus, artichoke etc... And want some solid vegetarian options... Look no further.  To put in perspective how good the food is here... It's the type of place where you literally have to fight the desire to lick the plate clean to not seem like a lunatic to people around you.

Very professional fresh made Egyptian food. The decoration from outside and inside is very unique Egyptian style. The chief is the owner of the place cooks every order while you wait. The food is very delicious and not expensive. Very nice Experience. They serve from 1 person alone up to a group of 30 but that would require a phone call "reservation"
Love the food and the service
Cash only. Cozy, eclectic place with very good food. It's usually only the chef doing everything so service can seem slow but he doesn't rush you along either even after you've paid.
Best Egyptian home made food ever!
Absolutely amazing. The chef is so sweet.
Delish Egyptian fare
Great food!
Great food, the chef loves to come and chat. Huge fan.

Not your average place. Dont be in a rush when you eat hete. It's takes a while as the very sweet owner takes your order and prepares your meal. Food was OK. Bit pricy but it's the experience that counts. Cash Only.
Good food and beautiful people serving you

Amazing restaurant. We went early afternoon on a weekday, when the restaurant was totally empty. Owner/chef is very nice, came and did small talk with us. Ask him what is good, like you would an Omakase chef. The specials were amazing. And he made a surprise for dessert, his own riff on kunafah.

Friendly/helpful staffs. Besides the menu, they can provide customized food. Foods are outstanding, had bone marrow, Egyptian sausage, fried brain, cattle cheeks, salmon wrapped in dough. The chef checked to see how was the food. He explained how the foods were prepared. Could tell that he has passion with cooking. The restaurant has interesting art work/decorations done by the chef. Will definitely come back to eat again.

Unpretentious, family run restaurant that serves good food. Had the lamb tagine and a baked eggplant dish, both served with cous cous. Both were satisfying. A tad pricey, but I don't mind paying a bit more for small family run places. The food took a while to prepare but the owner/chef (who was sweet and seemed like a kind person) was cooking and serving mostly by himself so it's understandable.
Delicious.
Pretty good food
This place is just all kinds of amazing in all kinds of ways.
Excellent family restaurant. Food is magnificent. Service is phenomenal. Owner and family are very nice and friendly. I would definitely recommend the place.

Mombar is a cozy, eclectic spot for home-style Egyptian food.  The atmosphere reminded me a lot of Cairo's alleyway holes-in-the wall.  You literally feel as though you've stepped into the chef's home as he prepares and serves you the food.  We went with the chef's special where the chef cooks you whatever he likes - giving you a heads up of whats to come when you place your order.  Started off with the usual mezze of babaganoush (eggplant), fool (fava beans) and hummus (chickpeas) with pita bread.  Next, we were served with four courses ranging from fish tajeen with couscous to lamb cheeks in a sauce to liver.  Definitely worth a try if you are an adventurous meat eater.

The owner is a very amicable host who cooks amazingly good home food. While everything we tried was very delicious, Lamb Tajeen Over Couscous left me speechless--I couldn't believe anything might taste that good! It was definitely worth the long ride I took to get there from Brooklyn.

This is the reason why Astoria exists. You simply can't get eclectic, cozy, mom & pop places like this in the city! Firstly, the exterior and interior of the restaurant are kooky, which adds a very definite charm to the eating experience. Secondly, the food boldly goes to new and exciting places in terms of cuisine offered stateside, and you'd be rewarded for trying out the adventurous fare (lamb cheeks? hell yes). Thirdly, the service was just great. The waiter was attentive, but not overbearing in the slightest. He knew exactly how to explain what separates each dish as well as when we needed more bread. And he let me and my friends really enjoy each others company for several hours. This place certainly takes its time, so I wouldn't recommend it if you're in a rush. But if you want a delicious meal with good company for hours on end, then come here.
It is a very unique place i wanna go there every day.

Best food in NYC ever! Atmosphere is unique, not ur regular boring type of restaurant with beige walls! The chef has made his own tables which unfortunately are not for sale. This place was featured in Antony Bordain's TV show for a reason!!!

Mombar is an eclectic little place - I feel like it was decorated with bits and pieces from a hoarder-grandmother's estate. But it works! Solid food and service and funky ambiance. Definitely a solid Astoria choice.
Very good Egyptian home cooking. Intimate and friendly ambiance; quirky and artsy decor (designed and built by owner from bric a brac).
Food was unimpressive, takes a long time, and they don't serve tap water. The staff was friendly though.
